itemprop="articleBody">\n<p>Crime may be at <a data-track="Body Text Link: Internal: dailyintel" href="http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2015/12/nycs-crime-rate-hits-a-new-record-low.html">an all-time low</a> in New York, but weird scary subway attacks are not.\xc2\xa0<a data-track="Body Text Link: Internal: dailyintel" href="http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2016/02/another-person-gets-slashed-on-the-subway.html">Eight</a>\xc2\xa0slashings have occurred so far this year, and Wednesday evening a woman at the Times Square subway station was reportedly attacked with a needle. <a data-track="Body Text Link: External" href="http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nyc-crime/woman-attacked-needle-times-square-subway-station-article-1.2519851?utm_content=buffer29e8e&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_source=twitter.com&amp;utm_campaign=NYDailyNewsTw">According</a> to the New York <em>Daily News</em>, the 37-year-old woman was on her way home at around 6:50 p.m. When she exited the subway station via the W. 49th Street and Seventh Avenue turnstile, she felt a man bump into her and a sharp pain in her shoulder. When she arrived home she discovered a puncture wound on that shoulder and checked into\xc2\xa0<span>Queens Mount Sinai Hospital for treatment.</span></p><p>An emergency-room doctor <a data-track="Body Text Link: External" href="http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nyc-crime/woman-attacked-needle-times-square-subway-station-article-1.2519851?utm_content=buffer29e8e&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_source=twitter.com&amp;utm_campaign=NYDailyNewsTw">reportedly</a> confirmed the wound was consistent with a needle, but exactly what the attacker used to puncture his victim\'s skin \xe2\x80\x94 whether a syringe, a sewing needle, or some other thin sharp object \xe2\x80\x94 is still unclear. Police are checking the surveillance recordings to get a better idea of what happened.</p>\n<p>This attack comes as cops are struggling to get a handle on the\xc2\xa0<a data-track="Body Text Link: Internal: dailyintel" href="http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2016/02/another-person-gets-slashed-on-the-subway.html">spike</a> in subway slashings, some of which have been\xc2\xa0<a data-track="Body Text Link: Internal: dailyintel" href="http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2016/02/another-person-gets-slashed-on-the-subway.html">spurred by arguments</a> and others of which <a data-track="Body Text Link: Internal: dailyintel" href="http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2016/02/another-person-gets-slashed-on-the-subway.html">appear to be random</a>. On Monday the Guardian Angels started patrolling trains for the first time in <a data-track="Body Text Link: External" href="http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2016/02/01/guardian-angels-subway-slashings/">more than two decades</a>, and the NYPD has <a data-track="Body Text Link: Internal: dailyintel" href="http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2016/02/another-person-gets-slashed-on-the-subway.html">upped</a> its presence on trains and platforms as well. Police Commissioner Bratton even proposed a (probably illegal) plan to bar "career criminals" from the subways. "We\'ll deal with it," he <a data-track="Body Text Link: External" href="http://gothamist.com/2016/02/02/man_slashed_in_the_chin_on_3_train.php">said</a> during an interview on Monday.</p></span></div>\n<footer><cite><a
